### Answers to Design Questions

**Q1: Constellation indicator -- ring stroke vs modify shadowColor?**

Ring stroke. An additional `Circle` with `stroke` and no `fill`, positioned at `r * 2.8` radius. Modifying the existing `shadowColor` would change the star's fundamental color identity (which is tied to the author's userId). A separate ring layer communicates "this star has connections" without altering what the star _is_. The ring is also `listening={false}` so it has zero interaction cost.

**Q2: Constellation glow lines -- Konva Line with shadowBlur vs Canvas2D Shape?**

Canvas2D `Shape` with `sceneFunc`. While Konva `Line` does support `shadowBlur`, it creates one shadow per node, and with the multi-layer approach we need, that would mean 3 Konva Line nodes per constellation link (already the case, and it results in many nodes). A single `Shape` batches all line drawing into one canvas pass, uses Canvas2D's native `shadowBlur` (which composites correctly with the strokes), and matches the proven pattern in `WormholeLayer.jsx` and the semantic bridges `Shape` in `InteractiveLayer.jsx`. The `Text` labels remain as Konva `Text` nodes because they need `scaleX/scaleY` zoom correction which is cumbersome in raw Canvas2D.

**Q3: Star titles -- SQL RPC vs posts Map?**

SQL RPC. The `find_wormhole_pairs` RPC already includes `a_title, b_title` by selecting from the same `journals` table it JOINs. The `get_viewport_constellations` RPC already JOINs `journals ja` and `journals jb` -- adding `ja.title AS a_title, jb.title AS b_title` costs zero additional query overhead. The posts Map is unreliable for this purpose because constellation links can span vast universe distances, and the linked star may never have been fetched in the current viewport session.

